# =============================================================================
# strongtalk — Animorphic Systems / Sun Microsystems'
#              "Strongtalk VM" — a high-performance
#              Smalltalk implementation with OPTIONAL
#              STATIC TYPING, originally developed at
#              Animorphic Systems (founded 1994 by
#              Urs Hölzle + Lars Bak + Robert Griesemer)
#              + acquired by Sun in 1997.  Strongtalk's
#              VM technology was the direct ancestor
#              of the HotSpot JVM (which became Java's
#              standard VM in 1999), V8 JavaScript
#              engine (Google's V8 was led by Lars Bak,
#              who also co-founded Strongtalk + later
#              Toit, R736), Dart VM, and most modern
#              high-performance dynamic-language VMs.
#              Strongtalk was open-sourced by Sun in
#              2006 as a historical artifact;
#              development paused in 1996 + briefly
#              resumed 2006-2021, with no active
#              development since 2021.  Still by far
#              the fastest Smalltalk implementation
#              ever measured — its JIT compiler +
#              type-feedback optimization techniques
#              were 5-10x faster than competing
#              Smalltalk implementations of its era.
#              Distinguishing from Squeak (image-based
#              dynamic Smalltalk, R692 trufflesqueak
#              GraalVM variant covered), Pharo (Squeak
#              fork), GNU Smalltalk (text-mode), VisualWorks
#              (Cincom commercial), VAST (formerly VA
#              Smalltalk), Newspeak (R712 SOMns), and
#              Smalltalk/X by:
#                - OPTIONAL STATIC TYPING — Smalltalk-
#                  80's pure dynamic typing extended
#                  with an OPTIONAL static type system
#                  ("strong typing")! Programmers can
#                  annotate types for runtime checks +
#                  better tooling, OR write fully-
#                  dynamic Smalltalk code, OR mix the
#                  two in the same codebase.  This
#                  pioneering design influenced TypeScript
#                  (JavaScript + optional types) +
#                  Dart (typed Smalltalk-influenced
#                  syntax)
#                - TYPE FEEDBACK + INLINING — Strongtalk's
#                  JIT compiler pioneered "type feedback"
#                  optimization: at runtime, the VM
#                  records which receiver classes are
#                  passed to message sends, then
#                  inlines + specializes the hot paths.
#                  Lars Bak's HotSpot JVM brought this
#                  technique to Java in 1999; V8 brought
#                  it to JavaScript in 2008
#                - 5 KEY VM CONTRIBUTORS — Urs Hölzle
#                  (later VP Engineering at Google,
#                  Google's longest-serving fellow),
#                  Lars Bak (HotSpot, V8, Dart, Toit
#                  R736), Robert Griesemer (Go
#                  language co-designer at Google),
#                  David Griswold + Gilad Bracha
#                  (Newspeak designer, R712).  Few VM
#                  projects have had such a star-
#                  studded contributor list
#                - IMAGE-BASED DEVELOPMENT — Smalltalk's
#                  traditional image-based development
#                  (Workspace, Inspector, Browser,
#                  Debugger) preserved + extended with
#                  type-annotation tooling
#                - BSD-LIKE LICENSE — open-sourced by
#                  Sun under a permissive license in
#                  2006; significant given that
#                  HotSpot JVM remained GPL until OpenJDK
#                  (2007)
#                - x86 ASSEMBLER (NASM) — VM
#                  implementation uses hand-written
#                  x86 assembly for the JIT compiler
#                  inner loops; portability is x86-only
#                - 3 CONFIGURATIONS — `strongtalk_debug`
#                  (C++ -O0, assertions on), `strongtalk_
#                  fast` (assertions off, partial
#                  optimization), `strongtalk` (full
#                  release optimization)
#                - .STRONGTALKRC CONFIG FILE — VM
#                  configuration options live in
#                  `.strongtalkrc` in the working
#                  directory; many options control
#                  JIT behavior, GC tuning, image
#                  loading
#                - STRONGTALK.BST IMAGE FILE — the
