# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 117TH LANGUAGE: STRONGTALK
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy expands its
# **117TH PROGRAMMING LANGUAGE**: Strongtalk (the Animorphic Systems /
# Sun Microsystems typed-Smalltalk + HotSpot/V8/Dart VM ancestor).
# This expands the taxonomy from 116 to 117 documented programming
# languages.
#
# Pattern: R737 Rust=92 (fddf/blake3 → Axis 37 OPENS) → R738 Go=92
# (go-spacemesh/zeebo-blake3) → R739 TS-Node=92 (flood/hash-wasm →
# Axis 37 CLOSES AT 1/1/1) → R740 117TH LANGUAGE (Strongtalk THIS).
# This completes the 3-leader-bump + 1-new-language micro-cycle.
#
# WHY STRONGTALK IS A DISTINCTIVE 117TH LANGUAGE:
#
#   1. OPTIONAL STATIC TYPING ON SMALLTALK — Strongtalk pioneered
#      the "optional static typing" paradigm IN A DYNAMIC LANGUAGE,
#      decades before TypeScript (2012), Python type hints (2014),
#      Sorbet for Ruby (2018), Dart's optional types, or Flow.
#      Strongtalk programmers could mix fully-typed + fully-
#      untyped Smalltalk code in the same program.  This design
#      space influenced all subsequent optional-typing efforts.
#
#   2. HOTSPOT JVM ANCESTRY — Animorphic Systems' VM team (Hölzle,
#      Bak, Griesemer, Griswold) joined Sun in 1997 + reused
#      Strongtalk's JIT + type-feedback techniques to build HotSpot,
#      Java's standard VM since 1999.  HotSpot is the most-deployed
#      Java VM in history.  Strongtalk is HotSpot's evolutionary
#      ancestor.
#
#   3. V8 JAVASCRIPT ENGINE ANCESTRY — Lars Bak led Google's V8
#      team in 2008-2011, applying Strongtalk + HotSpot techniques
#      to JavaScript.  V8 powers Chrome, Edge, Brave, Node.js,
#      Deno, Bun (partially), Electron, the entire Cloudflare
#      Workers stack, and ~70% of all JavaScript execution
#      worldwide.  Strongtalk is V8's evolutionary ancestor.
#
#   4. DART VM ANCESTRY — Bak + Kasper Lund continued the lineage
#      with Dart's VM at Google 2011-2018.  Flutter mobile apps
#      run on Dart VM.  Strongtalk is Dart's evolutionary ancestor.
#
#   5. TOIT VM ANCESTRY — Bak + Lund's most recent work (R736
#      Toit, 116th language).  Strongtalk is Toit's distant
#      evolutionary ancestor through Bak's continuous VM-
#      engineering career.
#
#   6. URS HÖLZLE PROVENANCE — Hölzle later joined Google as one
#      of the earliest engineers + became VP Engineering / Senior
#      Fellow.  His PhD work on Self language at Stanford (with
#      David Ungar) influenced Strongtalk; his Strongtalk work
#      shaped Google's infrastructure language designs.
#
#   7. ROBERT GRIESEMER PROVENANCE — Griesemer later co-designed
#      the Go language at Google (with Rob Pike + Ken Thompson).
#      Some of Go's design choices (simple type system, fast
#      compilation, no inheritance) reflect lessons learned from
#      Strongtalk's optional-typing experiment.
#
#   8. GILAD BRACHA PROVENANCE — Bracha later designed Newspeak
#      (R712 SOMns 110th language) at Cadence Design Systems,
#      taking Strongtalk's design lessons in a different direction
#      (pure capability-based, no globals, modules-as-classes).
#
#   9. TYPE FEEDBACK + INLINING — Strongtalk's JIT pioneered
#      runtime type-feedback collection + inline-caching +
#      polymorphic-inline-caches (PICs).  These three techniques
#      together represent perhaps the most important VM-research
#      contribution of the 1990s + form the foundation of every
#      modern dynamic-language VM.
#
#  10. 1996 INACTIVITY → 2006 OPEN SOURCE → 2021 DORMANT —
#      Strongtalk's history is one of "the wheel turns" — active
#      development 1994-1996 at Animorphic; absorbed into Sun
#      1997; HotSpot launched 1999; Sun open-sourced Strongtalk
#      2006 (10 years after development paused); brief community
#      revival 2006-2021; dormant since.  The CONCEPTS in
#      Strongtalk live on in HotSpot + V8 + Dart + Toit + TypeScript;
#      the VM itself is a historical artifact.
#
